h, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Matham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Mattins Farm in Radwinter or Martinfield Green in Saffron Walden (both Essex).","2  English: locative name from Mathon (Worcs).","3  English: nickname possibly from Middle English  <i>mathme</i>,  <i>mathom</i> ‘treasure, precious gift’ (Old English  <i>māðm</i>,  <i>maððum</i>), though the early bearers cited here may rather belong to (1) or (2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Mattam","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Matham  ."]},{"name":"Matthams","meanings":["English: variant of   Matham   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Samson","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name (Hebrew <i>Shimshon</i>, probably derived from <i>shemesh</i> ‘sun’), borne by a Jewish champion and judge famous for his prodigious strength. He was betrayed by his mistress, Delilah, and enslaved and blinded by the Philistines; nevertheless, he was able to bring the pillars of the temple of the Philistines crashing down in a final suicidal act of strength (Judges 13–16). This famous story provided the theme for  Milton's  poetic drama Samson Agonistes (  1671 ), which is modelled on ancient Greek tragedy. In the Middle Ages the popularity of the given name was increased in Celtic areas by the fame of a 6th-century Celtic saint who bore it, probably as a classicized form of some ancient Celtic name. He was a Welsh monk who did missionary work in Cornwall and afterwards established a monastery at Dol in Brittany."],"variants":[{"name":"Sampson","meanings":["Biblical name (Hebrew <i>Shimshon</i>, probably derived from <i>shemesh</i> ‘sun’), borne by a Jewish champion and judge famous for his prodigious strength. He was betrayed by his mistress, Delilah, and enslaved and blinded by the Philistines; nevertheless, he was able to bring the pillars of the temple of the Philistines crashing down in a final suicidal act of strength (Judges 13–16). This famous story provided the theme for  Milton's  poetic drama Samson Agonistes (  1671 ), which is modelled on ancient Greek tragedy. In the Middle Ages the popularity of the given name was increased in Celtic areas by the fame of a 6th-century Celtic saint who bore it, probably as a classicized form of some ancient Celtic name. He was a Welsh monk who did missionary work in Cornwall and afterwards established a monastery at Dol in Brittany."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Samson de Matham was born in 1304, in Molesey, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, his father, John de Matham, was 29 and his mother, Isabella de Molesey, was 27. He married Margaret de Surrey about 1339, in England. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. He died in 1358, in Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1304–1358":"1304–1358","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1340–1359":"1340–1359","1340–1382":"1340–1382","1342–1359":"1342–1359","1344–1359":"1344–1359","1346–1359":"1346–1359","1275–1333":"1275–1333","1277–1304":"1277–1304","1275":"1275","1340":"1340","abt 1340":"umbes 1340","1382":"1382","abt 1342":"umbes 1342","abt 1344":"umbes 1344","1304":"1304","abt 1346":"umbes 1346","1359":"1359","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1333":"1333","about 1339":"umbes 1339","1344":"1344","1277":"1277","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","of Surrey, Engl":"Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Molesey, Surrey, England":"Molesey, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","